images.alt: Hi! I'm a fan. I have truly enjoyed many of your essays. And as a trans woman, you're an inspiration. But I'm also Native American - specifically, a citizen of the Cherokee Nation. And I cannot stress enough how wrong you are about using "Indians" in the way that you have. While many Natives use that term themselves, amongst each other, it is a term we have fought being applied to us by others - especially colonizers. Please use Indigenous, Native American, First Nations, or specific tribal names. This advice isn't just mine, it's also what a cursory Google search turned up. So I'm struggling to believe you consulted with any Natives on this essay. Additionally, I take umbrage with your casual mention of the Beringial migration theory. While people certainly migrated through that channel, it's already widely disputed that that was our first appearance on this continent. Again, even some cursory research would have turned up things like Cooper's Ferry or Monte Verde. I think what's most disappointing in this essay is that it doesn't appear like you spoke to Natives. And that's about the most colonizer thing you can do. Please consider pulling this essay and editing it after a consult. There are some fantastic Native consultants that would be thrilled to help you out. Wado.
